  • info():
    • The info() method provides a concise summary of the DataFrame. It displays information such as the column names, data types, non-null counts, and memory usage. Here's what each output means:
      • Column names: The names of the columns in our dataset.
      • Data types: The data type (e.g., integer, float, string) of each column.
      • Non-null counts: The number of non-null (non-missing) values in each column.
      • Memory usage: The memory consumed by the DataFrame.

general structure of the data¶

This data is about passengers of RMS Lusitania, a British ocean liner that met a tragic fate during World War I. It was torpedoed and sunk by the German submarine U-20

And knwoing that which factors have more impact on being alive in this fate would be useful.

  • These dataset contains information such as

    • passenger survived or not,

    • ticket status,

    • traveling alone or no(siblings, spouses, parents, or children aboard)

    • passenger embarked place status

    • indevisial status(like gender, age, ...)

  • Number of passengers is 890

  • Data types are float, integer, object, boolean

  • Also some columns has overlap together.

Proportion of passengers that survived by class¶

sns.set(style='ticks', context='talk')
ax = sns.pointplot(x='class', y='survived', data=df, join=False, palette='Set2')
ax.set_ylim(0, 1)
sns.despine()

plt.xlabel("Ticket Class")
plt.ylabel("Proportion Survived")
plt.title("Proportion of Passengers Survived by Class")
plt.grid()

plt.show()

As we see, if class number decrease, fare paied decreases

This section confirms the previous section.

I used point plot because proportion is important.

  • Point plot

    • This method is used to show point estimates and confidence intervals using scatter plot glyphs.

    • A point plot represents an estimate of central tendency for a numeric variable by the position of scatter plot points

    • It provides some indication of the uncertainty around that estimate using error bars.

The formula to calculate the number of bins in a histogram is given by: $[ h = 2 \times \text{IQR} \times n^{-1/3} ]$ where:

  • $( h )$ is the number of bins,
  • IQR is the Interquartile Range of the data, which is the range between the 75th percentile and the 25th percentile,
  • $( n )$ is the total number of data points in the dataset.

By using this formula, you can determine an optimal number of bins for a histogram based on the dataset's characteristics.

In [20]:
n = len(df['Salary_USD'].unique())
IQR = (df['Salary_USD'].quantile(0.75) - df['Salary_USD'].quantile(0.25)) / 300
num_bins = int(2 * IQR * n **(-1/3))
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.histplot(df['Salary_USD'], bins=num_bins, kde=True)
plt.title('Distribution of Salaries')
plt.xlabel('Salary')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

def catplot(f1 , f2):
    if(f1 != f2):
        sns.catplot(x=f1, y='Salary_USD', hue=f2, data=df, kind='bar', height=6, aspect=2)
        plt.title(f'Salary Distribution by {f1} and {f2}')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.show()
    else:
        return
